<TITLE> Indonesia uncovers drug ring, arrests Malaysians </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 JAKARTA, Nov 23 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Indonesian police said they have arrested four suspected drug dealers, including two Malaysians, and seized ecstasy pills worth more than $5 million. The suspects, all men, face the death penalty if found guilty. Three of the men were arrested this week in Jakarta following a tip-off from a suspected drug dealer who was held earlier this month, the national police said in a statement. More than 480,000 ecstasy pills with an estimated street value of more than 49 billion rupiah ($5.23 million) were confiscated from the suspects, according to the statement. The police said the four men are believed to be members of an international drug syndicate, and they were now looking for two other Malaysians believed to be the syndicate's ringleaders. Indonesia imposes the death sentence for many narcotic offences, defending the penalty as necessary to deter others in a country with a growing drugs problem. Police said 3.2 million Indonesians are drug users and 15,000 of them die of drug abuse every year. ($1 = 9,365 rupi
